segments.text: member of the chow hall slam?
Oh, gosh.
Bread, butter, milk, gravy, beans?
Let me think a little bit.
It's been a long time that I don't remember that.
Do I remember any of those things?
I'll have to deal one if you want a piece of bread.
Milk?
It was cow.
Meat.
Meat.
I'm sorry.
Bull neck.
Bull neck.
Bull neck.
All right.
See, you know all of these things.
I don't remember.
Did you ever, when you were home, did you ever forget and say some of the things?
You want some shit on the shingle?
Yeah.
Yeah.
And what was the reaction of your family?
Again, by that time my father was dead and only my mother, and she was not one to be shocked.
It did not bother her.
Am I not correct that that was not an uncommon thing for an Aggie to forget?
Not uncommon at all, no, no.
It would be very common.
No, it would be quite common.
And in my particular case, it would not have come as a shock at all.
All right.
Now let's talk about academics.
You ended up majoring in?
Industrial engineering.
Industrial engineering.
Help please try to recall key faculty, counselors, advisors, et cetera.
Who were the people that made a difference for you?
The head of the...
I started out in a...
When I went into the course, it was called Management Engineering, and its name changed to Industrial.
And Arch Burgess was the head of the department, and he was a...
I can't describe how wonderful a department head he could be because he would work for his students.
He would do anything.
He would come.
He would work nights with you on projects.
He would come in and help you individually.
When I was a senior,
I had to, I again went to him and I said, I have to have a course, and I don't even remember what course it was, in order to graduate.
And it is not offered in this semester, which means I will have to go another entire year.
And he went to the, I guess, academic council, and he agreed.
He said, all right, I have gotten them to authorize the course for you.
I will meet with you, and we will discuss it.
And if you need any help, you call me for an appointment, and we will discuss it.
I will give you a mid-semester quiz.
I'll give you a project and an end-of-semester quiz.
And I ended up getting a B in the course.
I was the only enrollee.
I think that would be difficult today.
There are just too many students.
But he would do that.
He did it not only for me, he did it for other people that had the same kind of problem.
Others, add to that.
Oh.
God, I can see the man's face, but I can't remember his name.
He taught us statistics.
He was an older man.
And he taught us statistics.
And he...
He really, I guess, taught us to think.
What in the world is a man's name?
I can see his face.
I'll think of it in a minute.
He taught us statistics.
But while teaching us, he taught us statistics, but he taught us how to think.
What is his name?
Captain, Captain, Captain.
He was addressed by his military title.
Well, let's go on.
Other, chemistry, physics, math, English?
English.
A man by the name of Creswell who taught us literature and really, again, took some not very couth
kids from Waco and taught him to enjoy literature so that still today at any one time I'm reading two books at least and maybe three at any one time.
But he taught us to appreciate and enjoy reading.
I don't remember anything outstanding in math.
Chemistry, I enjoyed it every time I took it.
I had difficulty with chemistry.
Do you remember any of the instructions?
No.
Sorry.
But I just could not, chemistry never made sense to me and I think it took me three semesters to get a D. And I was so pleased with the D that it went home.
It was one of the mysteries of life.
over in a mechanical drawing slash et cetera shop.
We had to take shop as engineering in those days.
You had to be able to run a lathe.
You had to work in a foundry.
Engineers, I don't think, do that anymore.
They simulate it, perhaps, on a computer screen.
But we had to go do it hands-on.
And we always called the guys slide rule.
I can't remember the slide rule.
Can you remember any of the other faculty nicknames?
Sorry?
Cube Root Kent, Square Root Jackson.
Square Root Jackson is bigger than math.
That's something I've heard.
Supposedly, the number of students that have passed the course was the square root of .
Did you have any history?
Oh, yes, we had to take history, but again, nothing.
In those days, engineering, you took history courses because you had to take history courses.
You don't remember who you were.
No.
I had an elective in senior year, and I took a salesmanship course from a man by the name of Thompson.
And I took public speaking, which is one that
Something that I enjoyed.
I felt it was something that I need.
The other thing that I took, and his name was Spriggs.
That comes trippingly from the tongue.
I hope it's accurate.
But he taught public speaking, and I wanted that course.
These were electives in the engineering courses.
What were the unwritten rules about class attendance and behavior?
for you and your buddies?
Well, not to attend class and not to have a good excuse was a zero value for the day and anything that was homework that was late didn't matter.
If it was due on the day you didn't attend,
You got a zero.
You might attend and not have it done and get a dispensation to turn it in later.
But if you didn't come to class, it didn't matter.
You always addressed the instructor by the title, whether they were Mr. or Professor or Doctor.
you addressed always by title with a question.
It was formal, formal in those days.
And that's just the way it was done.
A teaching assistant, which you would see as a lab assistant in laboratories, could be addressed by a first name.
He's a doctoral candidate or a master candidate.
As you recall, were the faculty members accessible to you?
Yes.
Yes.
Anytime.
Anytime.
At home, office, on the campus.
Yes, they were.
They did a tremendous amount of one-on-one.
Yes.
Do you have any idea what it cost for you to go for a year or semester?
I have one thing that I've always enjoyed, and it's a story I've told so many times, and yes, I remember it.
When I enrolled as a freshman, you had to have $200, a diploma from an accredited high school, and be free of communicable disease.
That was the only requirement, but you had to have $200.
And that paid for a semester?
I guess it paid for a semester.
In your case, did you ever have an on-campus job?
Yes.
Where?
I worked for...
I spent most of my time working in the College of Agriculture.
The most memorable job being they were developing, spraying from aircraft.
And back over across the river in one of the fields, we would take eight and a half by eleven pieces of paper.
put them on little platforms across a field for maybe 200 yards and the aircraft would come in and would pass and spray back and forth.

Then you gather up all the pieces of paper where they were located and you took them in and you put them on a grid and then you counted the spots in the grid and you had to decide what was a big spot and what was a little spot.
And it was the decisions that killed me with the job.
But it was a good job and it paid well.
I don't remember how much it was, but it was a good paying job for that time.
It was a good paying job.
I worked for them for three years.
As far as you can recall, about how much spending money did you have to spend casually?
Oh, no more than five dollars a week, if that much.
No more than that.
What would you spend on casual food?
Junk food, entertainment.
Where did you get that?
Well, they had drink machines were there and so forth.
Vending apparatus were there.
both on campus and at the Air Force Base.
And then at Northgate, there were always places to spend your money.
And it didn't go to grind very much.
You could do anything you wanted to do at Northgate.
The YMCA was there.
Oh, yes.
What would it do?
What was that for?
Why?

I was never active in the YMCA, but they generally did, you know, to the best of my knowledge, if you had a problem or trouble, you would go to the Y, and they would find ways to help you, but I'm sorry.
Was Mr. Cashin still?
I don't know.
No, Ray Cashin.
Yeah, Ray Cashin.
MSC opened?
I think in the spring of my sophomore year, I went in the fall of 48, spring of 49.
I don't remember whether it was spring of 49 or the spring of 50 that it opened.
And it was wonderful with Bowling Alley and all of that.
It was something badly needed by the university and something that needs to be about 10 times its size today.
You have to understand that the basic building is unchanged from then.
You have 40,000 students trying to get into that building.
We had five.
What did the MSC mean in motion in 10X?
Did the word memorial, was that an important part of it?
The Memorial Student Center, yes.
It was important that it was a memorial because we were much closer to a major war than they are today.
We were much closer to the war that generated it.
There were even people who were students who were over there and had been shot in that war.
And then there were we younger people who had relatives that had died in that war.
And so the memorial park was more important to us than I'm sure it is today.
You and I are almost exactly the same age.
These old veterans from World War II.
You're talking about my brother.
They were living where?
Where did the vets live?
They lived in the older dorms, Law, Currier, the dorms, some that are gone now.
Then the married ones, where did they live?
The married ones lived down there on the south corner in the projects, and then across up the...
What do they call it up there behind what used to be the Ramada?
They were up in there.
There were two areas for married students.
What did you youngsters think about the veterans as fellow students?
They were just students.
Didn't think anything about them one way or the other.
They were just students.
It was fine.
Did they work hard?
Were they...
They were a challenge to us.
They were more dedicated.
We were still teenagers.
We were 18 and 19.
And they were in their upper ends of their 20s and usually in a hurry to get on with their lives.
And we weren't.
As far as you can recall, what did their lives do?
I wasn't.
I have no idea.
At 18, I probably didn't care.
I was assuming that many of them worked on campus at various places.
Oh, I'm sure they were the secretaries and so forth on campus.
I feel confident of that.
Did the MSC have a lot of activities early in its existence?
Yes.
Upstairs in the
I don't know what they call it now.
It was an auditorium at that time.
It had a stage and a ballroom.
But it had a stage and all of that.
And yes, they brought in the big bands of the day.
They played on that stage.
I can't remember any of the big bands.
But they were all well known.
And they came in.
You could dance there and on out.
It opened on to the roof of the building next to Terry's.
So you could handle several hundred up there at any one time.
Yes, it was the university, I think, worked hard to keep things going in that building.
And I think they did a very good job.
Were you aware of Wayne Stark then?
Wayne Stark was there.
You know, for me, he and I did not, we did not have any interaction at all.
What happened at Guy and Hall?
Well, that was movie theater.
Yes, there were movies there.
Guy, of course, is gone.
He's across the street from the park.
How often were there movies?
All the time.
Every day.
Every day.
It was just a running movie theater.
Did y'all go much?
Oh, yes.
Because you could go for...

nickels and dimes i don't remember the price but it was no cost and the movies changed twice a week and normally the audience was only students well you again you're running pretty much the first run movies so the this faculty and staff is there too they came oh yes because you're seeing whatever the first run yeah they've already played houston and dallas
But now they're in College Station at Guyon Hall and changing twice a week.
So faculty and staff and the local people, anybody want to come see a movie?
But sure, the big volume of people in the building would be students.
Let's see.
Let's talk about the student body in general.
If liberal means receptive change and conservative means hesitant acceptance of change,
Describe the student body in general.
We were conservative.
We were hesitant to change.
Hesitant to change tradition.
We came mostly from rural backgrounds, which are fought change.
Rich or poor?
Poor for the most part.
Protestant, Catholic, Jewish, what?
Protestant.
Heavily Protestant.
Very, very heavily Protestant.
Let's describe the student.
Do you remember some non-Anglo Protestant students?
A few Mexicans.
Mexican-American?
Mexican-American.
And how were they treated?
They were just students.
Now, we had black prejudice, perhaps, in those days.
We would not have wanted a black student there.
But most of us had gone to high school, and the Mexican-Americans were just students in high school.
And so they were just students there.
Did you have any Jewish students there?
I can't remember a name there as freshman.
We had, I do as junior and senior.
Yes, as junior and senior, yes.
And how were they treated?
It was just another guy.
Just another student.
I mean, again, I didn't find any religious prejudice.
And we're now talking about a religious prejudice.
And no, I think that
There was no Catholic prejudice.
Maybe I didn't see it.
Maybe it didn't occur to me to be prejudiced because of my upbringing.
But I knew nothing of prejudice for Catholic or for Jewish or for Mormon or whatever else you might say.
Were there any students from another country?
Were there any international undergraduate students?
I did not interact with them if there were.
They were not in my outfit and they were not in industrial engineering.
And in those days, as you narrowed down into junior and senior, you closed most of the rest of the world out from, except for your outfit and your department.
Let's see, we said, well to do or not, okay.
Religion.
There were a few wealthy ones.
A friend of mine from Fort Worth, Cullen Davis, came from a very wealthy family.
And Cullen was wealthy and his father sent he and his brothers to A&M
because he wanted them to be jerked up short from being rich kids.
And that's why he sent them down there.
They were nice guys.
And Cullen was in industrial engineering with me.
And that's, you know, we became friends there.
Let's see.
G. Raleigh is built after you?
Yes.
Yes.
So DeWare was the basketball game?
DeWare was the field.
Describe DeWare, kind of basketball game setting.
Did y'all go?
Oh, yes.
Yes.
Physically small.
As I recall, seats on only one side of the basketball court.
It was an old, old building.
But DeWare was not there yet, no.
The assembly hall still existed.
Where the chapel is now, right behind Law and Puryear, was the assembly hall.
It was a wooden building.
It still existed.
I was in the Aggie Players and we performed in the assembly hall.
Describe the Aggie Players.
What did they do?
It was, we did everything.
We did comedy, we did Greek, we did Oedipus and comedy.
Who was the director?
Or advisor?
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute.
He announced football games for everybody.
C.K.S.
C.K.S.
Describe him.
All right, you guys.
You guys are so damn stupid you couldn't learn anything.
I like C.K.
He was straightforward.
He didn't mince any words.
He wasn't polite.
He used whatever word was most appropriate.
He didn't care whether you liked it or not.
Is that a fair description of CK?
Where was his heart?
Everywhere.
You're inferring he cared about students?
Oh, yes.
Yes, yes, yes.
Now, as long as you did good, he'd say, ah, that's OK.
But if you did bad, he'd tell you everything you did wrong.
Now, was he the PA announcer at football?
I don't know.
I don't want to tell you the truth.
Forever after that.
Ten years later he was, I believe.
Yes, and forever after that he was.
Because I was there, but one day when he forgot to flip, he thought he'd flip the switch off.
He might have said anything.
I don't know what he said.
He did, and Mr.
Rudder sent a note for him to come to his office Monday morning.
And C.K.
went into the general's office.
Scared.
and let her stare the hole through it, and then burst out laughing.
And then said, now come on, C. Describe the, we're now on the main campus, and you're a sophomore or higher.
Describe the routine of a home football weekend.
What happened on Friday afternoon, night, and all day Saturday?
After class on Friday, you had dinner, and then there was Yelp, I guess.
And everybody formed up and marched to Yale practice at the Grove.
Is the bank shell still over at the Grove?
I think so.
Is it still there at the end of the drill field?
I think so.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I haven't noticed in years, to tell you the truth.
But you went to the Grove for Yale practice.
And with or without date, you might have a date.
If so, she was there.
And of course I got married while I was going to school.
So Mary Sue was there for Yale practice.
Now at what time?
Was this at midnight?
Yes.
Okay.
Yes.
And then it was usually back to the Student Center where there was some kind of entertainment going on.
And that was Friday night.
There generally were
By upperclassman time, you weren't scheduling Saturday classes.
You figured out how to get out of that track.
And so Saturday was a fairly sleep late day.
And you would then get ready for the game, which would normally be at 1 o'clock.
Because we wanted to get that game played without lights.
Lights.
I'm not even sure Kyle Field had lights.
I'm not certain of it.
It may have.
But I don't remember a game.
And you played a football game at 1 o'clock.
so that you were through by four o'clock and it's still light even late into the season and there's plenty of light for everything.
And that went, you went to the game.
If there was no game, if it was an away game and not a court trip, you probably didn't go to the game.
Again, transportation being difficult, expensive,

etc right now but let's go back saturday morning slept late you ate the noon meal about what time oh it was always served early probably by 11. and so you would then meet your date where oh depending on where she stayed you had to arrange for her to stay i was lucky in that i could generally get
get Mary Sue into a room at the Student Center.
You would plan ahead enough to make sure that you could get her into one there.
So we'd meet there.
And then go down to Duncan and eat.
And then go to the game.
You marched in.
I had to march in.
You took your date to the game, got her inside Playster.
Usually you then had to go back and you would catch your outfit en route.
just in time to march in, march around the thing.
As upperclassmen, you'd get away with that, freshman, sophomore, but.
Then as a Saturday night, what did y'all eat?
The usual things, maybe a movie, maybe if there was something on campus.
On a game night, they would usually, if it was good weather, have something at the Grove.
which could spill out again, some kind of music.
And you might dance, you might do nothing, you know, just one of those things.
It was... Do you remember going to the Cotton Ball?
Oh yes, yes.
Where was it?
The Cotton Ball was held in Sbisa because it was physically large.
And the Cotton Queen and so forth, there were delegates elected from other, girls elected from other universities to be delegates to the Cotton Ball.
And it went on.
And some girl ended up as the Cotton Queen.
And I don't even know what the selection process was.
What did a young man and young woman wear to the cotton ball?
A young man wore his uniform.
And a young woman would usually be in a long evening dress.
Full, you know, full evening dress.
How would you describe the behavior of people at the cotton ball?
Very formal.
Very formal.
As you would expect of the era.
How were young ladies treated?
Oh, my goodness.
As queens, they were of great respect.
Oh, yes.
They got a seat.
They had a drink.
They were taken care of.
They were waited on hand and foot.
Now, let's make believe you're dating a young lady.
Would you dance every dance with her?
Not necessarily.
How did you dance with someone else?
Usually you would interchange with a friend's date, and occasionally, the men always outnumbered the men, some of your friends who did not have dates would probably dance with yours at the time.
And the big bands were there.
Oh, yeah.
What were the other big dances?
There was a military...
